{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/python-for-beginners-control-statements-6feadf4ac4c", "time": 1683012130.657668, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/python-for-beginners-control-statements-6feadf4ac4c/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Python for Beginners \u2014 Control Statements | by Siva Ganesh Kantamani | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Python for Beginners \u2014 Control Statements", "description": "The world is often a complicated place to write a program that executes sequentially. No matter what project you\u2019re working on, it involves skipping few statements and then executing a series of\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/@sgkantamani", "anchor_text": "Medium", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/SG5202", "anchor_text": "Twitter", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://www.quora.com/profile/Siva-Ganesh-Kantamani-1", "anchor_text": "Quora", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/siva-kantamani-bb59309b/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://about.me/sivaganesh_kantamani", "anchor_text": "https://about.me/sivaganesh_kantamani", "paragraph_index": 25}, {"url": "https://sgkantamani.substack.com/p/subscribe", "anchor_text": "https://sgkantamani.substack.com/p/subscribe", "paragraph_index": 25}], "all_paragraphs": ["The world is often a complicated place to write a program that executes sequentially. No matter what project you\u2019re working on, it involves skipping few statements and then executing a series of statements recursively.", "This is where conditional statements in any language come to light; often, most languages have an if statement as a fundamental step to begin with, so does Python. Without any further delay, let\u2019s explore the different ways to write conditional statements in Python.", "In simple words, if statement is a combination of two components: expression and statement.", "expression: It\u2019s the condition that needs to evaluated and return a boolean (true/false)value.", "statement: statement is a general python code that executes if the expression returns true.", "The syntax of if statement looks, as shown below:", "Always remember colon(:) following the expression is mandatory, to put it into the action we can do something as shown below:", "We can also execute multiple statements if the expression returns true, Have a look:", "To make it fun, we can write various statements in a single line by separating them with a semi-colon, have a look:", "We can also use the if statement to check whether a value is in the dictionary or not using in operator. Have a look:", "Using the if statement, we can execute a selected set of statements, but what if we want to execute another set of statements when the condition fails? That\u2019s when else come in. Have a look at the syntax:", "Similar to if statement we need to use a colon(:) after else and maintain indentation, look at a simple example:", "To make things a bit more complicated, what if we need to check more than one condition? That\u2019s is when elif comes to light. elif acts as a combination of if /else blocks.", "If the preceding condition(s) fails and the present expression is satisfied, then the block of statements under elif block executes. Have a look at the syntax:", "Let\u2019s write a simple piece of code to understand it better.", "Until now, we\u2019ve seen the universal solutions; to make things a bit more pythonic, we can use get function on dictionaries. This process involves including necessary conditions and outputs in the dictionary as key-value pairs.", "To better understand it, let\u2019s us write a simple example, have a look:", "Here the dictionary emojis acts as a key-value pair that indicates the expression and statement execute. When we invoke get function on the dictionary with input as the first argument, it\u2019ll check for the key with that value. If found, it prints the value of the key else prints the second argument. Here the second argument acts as else case.", "Python introduced a ternary operator to keep things minimal. In other words, we can say it is the simplest form of writing if / else block.", "When we deep dive into control statements, there three main things we need to consider: conditional expression, positive result, and negative result. The whole conditional execution revolves around them. Let\u2019s see the syntax of the ternary operator in Python:", "This operator aims to reduce the boilerplate code and create a more concise and readable program. Let\u2019s write a simple example using the ternary operator:", "To learn more about Python from basics to advanced read following articles", "That is all for now, hope you learned something useful, thanks for reading.", "You can find me on Medium, Twitter, Quora and LinkedIn.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Learn. Code. Write. Repeat. Visit me at https://about.me/sivaganesh_kantamani & Join my email list at https://sgkantamani.substack.com/p/subscribe"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6feadf4ac4c&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fpython-for-beginners-control-statements-6feadf4ac4c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fpython-for-beginners-control-statements-6feadf4ac4c&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------",